  <h1 class="hidetitle">Pebbles on the Beach</h1> 
  <h2>Keeping hold of the big questions</h2> 
  <h3>George V. Neville-Neil</h3> 
  <br /> 
  <p><b>Dear KV,</b></p> 
  <img src="https://spawn-queue.acm.org/cms/10.1145/3818306/asset/72b65769-1aea-4e9e-915c-2e4647d1e84a/assets/images/medium/3818306_uf01.jpg" alt="pebbles" style="float:right;width:25%;max-width:640px;padding:0px 0px 20px 20px;" /> 
  <p>I know that your column is mostly for practitioners, but I have a question about academia for you. So, I hope it’s OK if I throw you a bit of a curveball question.</p> 
  <p>I’ve been working as a research engineer in a university computer science department. This is my first job out of college—although “out” is a bit wrong since I’m still at the same institution where I got my undergrad degree. I thought I’d spend some more time here building things for people while I decide whether to pursue a graduate degree or go into industry. Everyone seems very worried about LLMs and AI and all that, but I did a senior project with a professor here and she had funding for a position for a year and asked if I wanted to stick around. So, I did.</p> 
  <p>The work is a continuation of the project I was already on, only now I’m better paid and share an office with a grad student who is also working on the same project.</p> 
  <p>One of the things I’ve been trying to pick up, along with some new data analysis and scientific Python skills, is how researchers go about choosing or finding problems to study. There’s a group lunch each week, and the grad students present what they’re working on and get comments from my boss, along with a few other professors. But it all seems very open ended, as if they’re just making it up as they go along. I even asked the grad student I’m sharing the office with, and his response wasn’t quite as obnoxiously Zen as something from Yoda, but it was something like, “I just wander around the space picking up rocks and looking under them until I find a problem that interests me, and then I build some small prototype to see if the idea has merit.” When I pressed him on how he judged merit, the best I got was, “Can I think of a journal or conference that would publish what I want to write about?”</p> 
  <p>Now I have this image of researchers wandering around with colorful sand pails, picking up pebbles on a beach, and seeing which ones they want to take home. Since I don’t have any other academic experience to compare it with, I wonder if this pertains to just this group or is more widespread. I know from your bio that you work with universities. So, is this common, or is it just my group?</p> 
  <p align="right" style="text-align:right"><b>– Pebbles on the Beach</b></p> 
  <p><b>Dear Pebbles,</b></p> 
  <p>You read my bio? What did it say? Hopefully nothing too salacious, although cavorting with academics might be considered... well, never mind.</p> 
  <p>On the one hand, I could be equally vague and say, “There are as many intellectual styles among academics as there are grains of sand.” But, in fact, that has not been KV’s experience in his time as someone who has done, as you do, development for research.</p> 
  <p>Research is often billed as being “curiosity driven.” And, with the recent attacks on academia, particularly in the United States, this phrasing has even made its way into the popular press. For the whole of human history, some people have been curious about the world around them, and they have come up with different ways to satisfy that curiosity. Newton is said to have stuck a needle around his eyeball to “learn about colour” (his spelling, not mine). You have to really be interested in how your eye works to mess with it in that way.</p> 
  <p>Now, the real question is: Was Newton just idly walking one day when he thought, “Cheerio, if I shove a needle into my eye socket, will I get a minimum publishable unit for the <i>Journal of Crazy Eyeball Physics and Optics</i>?” I kind of hope this was not what he was thinking, and I also kind of hope Newton didn’t sound like some parody of Monty Python either. Rather, KV hopes Newton had a question he was trying to answer about the nature of light, or the nature of how we perceive light.</p> 
  <p>This is where we come to what KV has seen from the best researchers: They’re not just wandering around picking up shiny pebbles; instead they are trying to answer some particular question. Answering questions is what scientists—and engineers—are supposed to do. Which provides us with a crossover between science and practice.</p> 
  <p>When KV is debugging a piece of code (which is most of what he does, since he works on large codebases written by 12 monkeys with ASR-33 terminals who were trying to hammer out a copy of Version 7 Unix by typing randomly), he too is trying to answer a question. The top-level question KV most often faces is: Where is my gin? But shortly after that, the next lower-level question arises: Why does this code suck? Then that evolves into something more sedate: Why does this function return garbage but only after more than a million correct operations?</p> 
  <p>We see here the effect of the question on the eventual solution. This is why the polestar KV uses to keep him on track is: What is the problem we are trying to solve?</p> 
  <p>Should you ever lose track of this guiding star, you will get lost in a universe of dull red dwarfs, bright new blue suns, neutron stars, and the most dreaded star of all—the black hole.</p> 
  <p>It has been my privilege over the years to work with some academics for whom this question of focus is always firmly in mind. They may have ideas about how to answer a question, in part, because of happenstance—the equivalent of picking up a shiny pebble on the beach is very much the “Aha!” moment in the shower, but this is not what is guiding them. The guiding star is a question such as: Why do all systems seem to reduce to this one type of system? What is the optimal layout of this set of data structures? How can we build an interface that is usable by nonspecialists and yet does not impede the specialist user? And, of course, since KV is a “systemsy” person, How can I make this system perform more operations per unit of time than it already performs?</p> 
  <p>If KV had been a physicist, which might have been the case had he been smarter, then the questions would have been grander: Where did the universe come from? Can anything travel faster than light? And the perennial, Where is my other sock? I put a pair in the dryer and now I only find one.</p> 
  <p>There are many advantages to this question-focused form of research, not the least of which is that it can lead to a longer-term program than a single, shiny pebble might. KV was very young when he was first exposed to the people building BSD Unix at UC Berkeley, a project they had already been working on for many years, which had not only produced useful working systems for others, but also led to answers to several questions about software design, process scheduling, and file storage, among others. While the group might not have used the same terms KV is using here (and they definitely would not use the same words KV uses when he’s angry at code), one can see that the questions they asked led to much of the research they produced. KV continues to seek out researchers who are question-focused in this way because questions also lead to narratives, and KV hates work without a narrative arc.</p> 
  <p>The need for a narrative arc is a personal bias. Not everyone needs one, but there are fewer things more maddening than watching someone wander around a space bumping into ideas as if they’re in a pinball machine, learning nothing more than a few words that might be used at a cocktail party to impress the guests. To develop ideas that coherently answer questions, there must be order—and that order is the narrative arc.</p> 
  <p>If you find that you as well need this form of order to organize thoughts and you like to keep a good question in front of you to guide you, then, by all means, continue your work with academics. Look for the ones who don’t just publish papers on a particular topic, but those who develop full programs that attract bright graduate students who understand the <i>research question</i>, as they call it, and then take a piece of that question and try to answer it. This is the way in which the edifice of science has been built. Picking up pebbles on the beach is a hobby, but answering questions is a calling.</p> 
  <p align="right" style="text-align:right"><b>– KV</b></p> 
